Does $\blueD{(9 \times 2) \times 5}=\purpleC{9 \times 10}?$

$
\begin{align}
\blueD{(9 \times 2) \times 5} &\stackrel{?}{=}  \purpleC{9 \times 10}
\\\\
\blueD{9 \times (2 \times 5)} &\stackrel{?}{=}  \purpleC{9 \times 10} &&\text{Associative property of multiplication}\\\\
\blueD{9 \times 10} &=  \purpleC{9 \times 10}
 \end{align}$

Yes, $\blueD{(9 \times 2) \times 5}$ is equivalent to $\purpleC{9 \times 10}$.

Does $\blueD{(9 \times 3) \times 3}=\purpleC{9 \times 9}?$

$
\begin{align}
\blueD{(9 \times 3) \times 3} &\stackrel{?}{=}  \purpleC{9 \times 9}
\\\\
\blueD{9 \times (3 \times 3)} &\stackrel{?}{=}  \purpleC{9 \times 9} &&\text{Associative property of multiplication}\\\\
\blueD{9 \times 9} &=  \purpleC{9 \times 9}
 \end{align}$

Yes, $\blueD{(9 \times 3) \times 3}$ is equivalent to $\purpleC{9 \times 9}$.

Does $\blueD{7 \times 3\times 3}=\greenD{(7 \times 3) + (7 \times 3)}?$

$
\begin{align}
\blueD{7 \times 3 \times 3} &\stackrel{?}{=}  \greenD{(7 \times 3) + (7 \times 3)}
\\\\
\blueD{21 \times 3} &\stackrel{?}{=}  \greenD{21 + 21} &&\\\\
\blueD{21 \times 3} &\neq  \greenD{21 \times 2}
 \end{align}$

No, $\blueD{7 \times 3\times 3}$ is not equivalent to $\greenD{(7 \times 3) + (7 \times 3)}$.

Does $\blueD{7 \times 3\times 3}=\purpleC{7 \times 9}?$

$
\begin{align}
\blueD{7 \times 3 \times 3} &\stackrel{?}{=}  \purpleC{7 \times 9}
\\\\
\blueD{7 \times (3 \times 3)} &\stackrel{?}{=}  \purpleC{7 \times 9} &&\\\\
\blueD{7 \times 9} &=  \purpleC{7 \times 9}
 \end{align}$

Yes, $\blueD{7 \times 3\times 3}$ is equivalent to $\purpleC{7 \times 9}$.
